[[File:Onsen Jinja Iwaki Torii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|鳥居}}]]
'''Onsen Jinja''' (温泉神社) is a {{ill|Shinto Shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft}} {{ill|Iwaki|ja|いわき市|12=draft}}. It is a small {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内小社|12=draft}} as listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}}, and under the {{ill|Modern Shrine Ranking System|ja|近代社格制度|12=draft}} it was designated as a prefectural shrine. It serves as the guardian shrine of {{ill|Yumoto Onsen|ja|湯本温泉|12=draft}}.

== History ==
=== Overview ===
According to the shrine tradition, the shrine was originally enshrined at Yunodake (Sabako Peak, 三箱山), located 5 km northwest of the present site. It is said that in {{ill|Hakuhō|ja|白鳳|12=draft}} 2 ({{ill|673|ja|673|12=draft}}) the first priest, 小子部宿禰佐波古直足, transferred the enshrinement to Yumoto Sanhako, marking the establishment of the shrine. In the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}} it was classified as a small shrine. In {{ill|Ryakuō|ja|良応|12=draft}} 3 ({{ill|1340|ja|1340|12=draft}}) it was moved to Kannon-yama (located to the north of the current site), and later in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|12=draft}} 5 ({{ill|1768|ja|1768|12=draft}}) it was relocated to its present location. Under the modern shrine Ranking system, it was designated as a prefectural shrine.

=== Divine Rank ===
* In {{ill|Jōgan|ja|承和|12=draft}} 5 ({{ill|863|ja|863|12=draft}}) on {{ill|October 29|ja|10月29日|12=draft}}, it received the Rank of Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade (as recorded in the ''{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft}}'').

=== Shrine Clergy ===
From ancient times, '''Sabako-shi''' (佐波古氏) has continuously held the hereditary position of shrine priest. The origin of the shrine’s alternate name, Sabako Shrine, is attributed to the fact that the shrine enshrines Yunodake (Sabako Peak) as its sacred mountain ({{ill|Shintaizan|ja|神体山|12=draft}}) and the hereditary priestly family is the Sabako-shi.

== Shrine Facilities ==
The main hall was constructed in {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|12=draft}} 8 ({{ill|1695|ja|1695|12=draft}}) and has been designated as a tangible cultural property by Iwaki City.

